rename.to: [SETUP-BUG] Table schema in latest_schema.sql gives errors on Microsoft SQL Server

body: @arees88 Copying the `latest_schema.sql` file should not be necessary / is not the recommended approach for using the SQL Tracking backend. Can you try setting your MLflow tracking URI to point to a fresh SQLServer database via `mlflow.set_tracking_uri()` and then attempt to log to MLflow?

@arees88 That's correct! For reference, please check out the constructor of the `SqlAlchemyStore` class (https://github.com/mlflow/mlflow/blob/07d2b4a1a13f9245d1519423ad775a2e064faecb/mlflow/store/tracking/sqlalchemy_store.py#L66). I'm going to go ahead and close this issue; feel free to re-open it if you're still running into issues.

@dbczumar That's what I did last year with 0.91 but did not get very far because of the  'lifecycle_stage' column being duplicated bug. Hence I created the tables directly on the DB and after a few other fixes in the code everything worked fine. 

Re: 1.5.0
I have run one of the example scripts to initialise the tables in the database:

python examples/sklearn_elasticnet_wine/train.py

I did not get very far this time either. The execution stopped with the NotImplementedError exception in:
lib\site-packages\sqlalchemy\engine\interfaces.py", line 413, in get_check_constraints
      raise NotImplementedError()

Looks like the implementation for SQLAlchemy interface methods is missing or not found.

Please note, I have initialised the MLFLOW_TRACKING_URI  to point to an empty DB, so not sure why all the migration steps were triggered, as it is seen in the trace below:
